 economic and political traditionalism that stymied growth and adaptation. The result was a system heading toward collapse as planters, facing a series of larger crises in the French empire, vainly attempted to rein in the inherent violence and instability of the slave society they had built. In recovering the lost world of the French Antillean plantation, Cul de Sac ultimately reveals how the capitalism of the plantation complex persisted not as a dynamic source of progress, but from the inertia of a degenerate system headed down an economic and ideological dead end.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCapitalismzHaitixHistoryy18th century. 0aPlantation overseers - Haiti. 0aPlantation overseerszHaiti. 0aPlantation ownerszHaiti. 0aSugar plantationszHaitizCul-de-Sac PlainxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aFerron de la Ferronnays.  aFrance.  aHaitian Revolution.  aSaint-Domingue.  aearly modern capitalism.  aplantation complex.  aslavery.  asugar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022607935640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226411774423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226411774/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles